Jesus' birth.

It's not a fictional story in a book full of outdated words... words that don't pertain to us in this time.

His birth was foretold and documented hundreds of years before...
where he would be born, that his mother would be a virgin, even his name.

Perfect Jesus humbled himself and came to this earth as an infant, miraculously born of a virgin. 

He was love in human form. He lived among us. Breathed our air. Walked our ground. He hungered. He wept. He knew our pain. Healed the sick. He brought joy.

He loved.

He also rocked the boat and brought truth...
something that, unfortunately, doesn't always go over well with humanity.

It led to an uprising. It led to 33 years of life being ended on a cross.

But that was always the plan. 

God sent Jesus to ultimately give his life for you and for me. 

Think about it- Jesus died willingly. He did not fight.

He WENT to the cross. 

Why? 

Because he loves you. He knew that your only hope for freedom was through him. His sacrifice on the cross paid the debt for our sin. 

God chose this to save humanity and to give us a place in heaven with him. He planned it, so that we can have a relationship with him....not a relationship only when we get to heaven, but right now.

Perfect Jesus became our sin on the cross. But that paved the way for past, present, and future sin to no longer define us and lead us to Hell...a real place...a place we don't like to think or talk about, but real nonetheless. 

Good news!! When we choose him, choose to believe, choose his gift of salvation, we have Him living with us and in us. We are granted access to a Father who loves us unconditionally more than we could ever even imagine. 

So you see....the birth of Jesus and why we celebrate today, isn't only about a baby who was born in a manger, but a man who gave his life for you and for me. A man who didn't stay in a tomb, but died and miraculously rose again. 

His name means "God with us" and he truly is, if we choose him too. 

He already chose you. 

Open your Bible with me in this new year. Look through His love letter to us, and make it personal. We all need more Truth, Light and Love in our lives.

I always say "It's the room I dreamed about most when we were living in our barn for 10 years." 

And I mean it. 

I had no windows in my barn kitchen. Just a slanted wall/ceiling in my face from the gambrel style barn roof. No lighting above the sink. Just a desk lamp on top of the fridge. One hand-me-down counter about 5 feet long with two cabinet doors underneath. A makeshift pantry with curbside, hinged closet doors. 

But we made the most of it. We became a family and were blessed with our son in that barn (yes! He can say he was raised in a barn, literally) and I dreamed of the day we would start our house that we sketched on graph paper. 

Ten years was a long time to live in an 800 SQ ft barn apartment, but 4 years of that time was spent working in our house when we had the funds. 

We've been here 7 years, and it's still not complete. It's not grand. Rather simple actually. But it's ours. From the ground up, it's got our fingerprints in every nook and cranny. Every nail/screw. Every piece of wood. Every stroke of paint. I look at this place and walk in the front door oh so often and thank the Lord that he gave us this little place in the woods. 

Thank you for watching and reading. 💕💕💕

Potatoes and onions are in the baskets in the island, in case you were wondering. 

The crate came from my grandma's kitchen. She had it stacked with some other things next to her island. 

She loved decorating her house. She wallpapered and painted, we went shopping for curtains, shopping for bedding.... She moved furniture, changed tchotchkes from here to there, loved her houseplants and beautiful yard.... made quilts, collected milk glass, enjoyed cooking and baking, and loved deeply. 

If the internet and Instagram were around when she was younger, she would have been here, sharing her sweet, little house, making everyone laugh. She always made people laugh. I miss her so much, but I'm grateful she's in heaven with Jesus.

I am thankful too, that I had her for so long, that I was able to soak up so much of who she was, that my husband tells me all the time that I remind him of her. 

There's no one I'd rather be like. 

Enjoy your Sunday, my friends. Squeeze those you love and hold tightly to those memories.

I've had this geranium for years and years. It has bloomed several times for me when there was still snow on the ground. The smell of the leaves, the leggy overgrown manner in which it hangs from its pot, the pop of color...... All of it. It's been my favorite indoor wild thing for a long time.

It's called many things: carousel, pyramid, windmill. 

The history always intrigues me.

The science too:

When a candle burns, the flame heats the nearby air and starts to rise. As this warm air moves up, cooler air and oxygen rush in at the bottom of the flame to replace it.

When that cooler air is heated, it too rises up and is replaced by cooler air at the base of the flame.

This creates a continual cycle of upward moving air around the flame (a convection current).
source: candles.org

But then there's just the magic of it all. 

Such a nostalgic and beautiful Christmas decoration to watch. I remember buying it at a garage sale. The lady was so sweet to come down on price when I said that I was buying it for my little boy (now 18). This will be his one day. 

It's mesmerizing! Even sweeter knowing that it tells the story of Jesus' birth.
